{"title_page": "Boogeyman 2", "text_new": "{{about|the 2007 horror film|the unrelated 1983 film|Boogeyman II}}\n{{featured article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Boogeyman 2\n| image = Boogeyman2.jpg\n| alt = Poster feature the film's lead, a young blonde woman, lying on a bed and facing the camera with the Boogeyman being under her bed.\n| caption = DVD cover\n| director = [[Jeff Betancourt]]\n| producer = {{plainlist|\n* Steve Hein\n* Gary Bryman\n}}\n| writer = Brian Sieve\n| starring = {{plainlist|\n* [[Danielle Savre]]\n* [[Matt Cohen (actor)|Matt Cohen]]\n* [[David Gallagher]]\n* [[Mae Whitman]]\n* [[Renee O'Connor]]\n* [[Tobin Bell]]\n}}\n| music = [[Joseph LoDuca]]\n| cinematography = Nelson Cragg\n| editing = Jeff Betancourt\n| studio = [[Ghost House Pictures]]\n| distributor = [[Sony Pictures Home Entertainment]]\n| released = {{Film date|2007|10|20|Screamfest Horror Film Festival|2008|01|08|United States|2008|06|05|Russia}}\n| runtime = 89 minutes<ref>{{cite web|title=Boogeyman 2 (2007) |url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/boogeyman-2-2007 |publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |accessdate=May 22, 2017 }}</ref>\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| budget = $4.5 million<ref>{{cite web|title=Boogeyman 2 |url=http://bloody-disgusting.com/horrordb/movies/boogeyman-2/ |work=[[Bloody Disgusting]] |publisher=The Collective |accessdate=March 19, 2017 }}</ref>\n| gross = $4.3 million<ref name=\"Gross\">{{cite web|title=Boogeyman (2008) |url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Boogeyman-2#tab=video-sales |website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |publisher=Nash Information Services, LLC |accessdate=March 18, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150920005749/http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Boogeyman-2 |archivedate=September 20, 2015 }}</ref><ref name = \"Int gross\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''Boogeyman 2''''' is a 2007 American [[supernatural horror film]] edited and directed by [[Jeff Betancourt]] and the [[sequel]] to the 2005 film ''[[Boogeyman (film)|Boogeyman]]''. The film was written by Brian Sieve and stars [[Danielle Savre]], [[Matt Cohen (actor)|Matt Cohen]], [[Tobin Bell]] and [[Renee O'Connor]]. Savre portrays Laura Porter, a woman who witnessed her parents' murder alongside her brother as a child. She believes the killer to be the [[Bogeyman|Boogeyman]], and now as an adult seeks group therapy to overcome her phobia of the creature. However, her fears become reality as her fellow patients are murdered one by one.\n\nDue to the previous film's financial success, ''Boogeyman 2'' was announced in October 2006. Production of the film began in the same month with the hiring of Betancourt as director and Sieve attached as writer. Casting began in December of the same year with the hiring of O'Connor; Savre got the lead role in January 2007. Filming took place in [[Los Angeles]] at the former hospital, [[Linda Vista Community Hospital]], over a four-month period, beginning in January 2007 and concluding in April. Unlike the original film, which featured the Boogeyman as a supernatural being, Betancourt strove to present a more grounded and realistic version of the mythical creature. Additionally, emphasis was placed on the writing and atmosphere to compensate for the film's small $4.5 million budget.\n\nAfter screening at the [[Screamfest Horror Film Festival]] on October 20, 2007, ''Boogeyman 2'' was released [[direct-to-video]] in the United States on January 8, 2008; it was later released theatrically in Russia and Italy. It received mixed reviews from critics, although many of them considered it to be a general improvement over its predecessor. Attention was especially given to the human-like nature of the Boogeyman in the film, which reviewers felt was preferable to monsters in other contemporary [[Creature Features|creature features]], including the previous film. Despite a mediocre commercial performance, recouping slightly less than its budget, the film received a sequel, ''[[Boogeyman 3]]'', the following year.\n\n==Plot==\nAs young children Laura Porter and her brother Henry witness their parents' brutal murder by a hooded man, whom they believe to be the [[Bogeyman|Boogeyman]]. As an adult, Henry has attended group therapy, improving such that he is instead currently looking for work. Laura joins this group as he leaves, meeting the other members: [[Nyctophobia|nyctophobic]] Mark, [[Germaphobia|germaphobic]] Paul, [[Self-harm|masochistic]] Alison, [[Agoraphobia|agoraphobic]] and commitment-averse Darren, and Nicky, a [[bulimic]] girl who fears extreme weight gain.\n\nUpon her joining, however, the members of the group are targeted and murdered one by one. All of their deaths relate to their fears: Mark falls down an elevator shaft, trying to escape from the darkness when the lights go out, and is torn in half. Paul accidentally consumes a cockroach while eating a bag of chips; he is given cleaning solution by a masked figure, and upon drinking it, burns a hole in his throat. Laura begins to suspect these deaths are not accidental. The hospital loses power, leaving Laura, Alison, Darren, Nicky, Dr. Jessica Ryan, and the receptionist Gloria in the dark. Gloria goes to the basement to turn the lights back on, but once the patients return to their rooms, Alison is tied to her bed by the Boogeyman. He places maggots on her arms, which burrow into her skin via her self-inflicted incisions, and she kills herself attempting to cut them out.\n\nDr. Ryan goes to the basement to check on Gloria, but is electrocuted by the Boogeyman while standing in a puddle of water. Laura finds a file on her brother and those of other patients with bogyphobia ([[phobia]] of the Boogeyman). She learns that all bogyphobia patients - including Tim Jensen, the protagonist of the first film - have committed suicide after being treated by Dr. Mitchell Allen. Darren and Nicky have sex in the locker room as Laura finds Alison; she alerts them to Alison's corpse, but they find upon returning that the blood and maggots have been cleaned up, leading them to believe that Laura is [[Hallucination|hallucinating]]. Darren and Nicky go to his room, where they argue about the viability of their relationship. Darren forces Nicky out of his room, and is then attacked by the Boogeyman, who disembowels him and removes his heart.\n\nLaura finds Nicky on a basement table with hoses attached to her, pumping bile into her body until she explodes. The Boogeyman chases Laura through the hospital; along the way she finds Gloria's body and Dr. Ryan, barely alive and mumbling in a trance-like state. She also runs into Dr. Allen, who believes Laura committed the killings. He tries to sedate her, but is stopped by the Boogeyman, who stabs him and shoves two needles into his eyes. The Boogeyman is revealed to be Henry; Dr. Allen had locked him in a closet in an attempt to treat him of his bogyphobia, and the Boogeyman possessed Henry at that time. The chase ends when Laura decapitates the Boogeyman with gardening shears. The police arrive and discover that under the Boogeyman mask was Dr. Ryan; after killing Dr. Allen but prior to chasing Laura, Henry put the mask on the doctor and escaped. Laura realizes that Henry is running free and is framed for the murders and arrested.\n\nIn a [[post-credits scene]], the Boogeyman looks at a picture of Laura and Henry as adults before disappearing.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Danielle Savre]] as Laura Porter\n* [[Matt Cohen (actor)|Matt Cohen]] as Henry Porter\n* [[Tobin Bell]] as Dr. Mitchell Allen\n* [[Renee O'Connor]] as Dr. Jessica Ryan\n* Chrissy Griffith as Nicky\n* [[Michael Graziadei]] as Darren\n* [[Mae Whitman]] as Alison\n* [[Johnny Simmons]] as Paul\n* [[David Gallagher]] as Mark\n* [[Lesli Margherita]] as Gloria\n* [[Tom Lenk]] as Perry\n* [[Sammi Hanratty]] as Young Laura Porter\n* Jarrod Bailey as Young Henry Porter\n* Lucas Fleischer as Mr. Porter\n* Suzanne Jamieson as Mrs. Porter\n* Christopher John Fields as Detective\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development and filming===\n[[File:Boogeyman 2 - Boogie Mask.jpg<!-- Don't resize non-free images per WP:NFCCP -->|thumb|right|Evolution of the killer's mask, dubbed \"Boogie Mask\", throughout various stages of development. Ranging from concept art (''left''), to early build (''center'') and the finished product (''right'').|alt=Three images showing featuring the killer wearing a mask in: a drawing (left), mold (center) and final film design (right). The mask covers the entire face and has huge teeth where the mouth is. In the final film, the killer also wears a black hoodie.]]\n\n''Boogeyman 2'' was first announced in October 2006 due to the financial success of its predecessor with [[Jeff Betancourt]], [[film editing|film editor]] of ''[[The Exorcism of Emily Rose]]'', ''[[When a Stranger Calls (2006 film)|When a Stranger Calls]]'' and ''[[The Grudge 2]],'' making his directorial debut and Brian Sieve attached as writer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/boogeyman-2-is-creeping-up-on-us/ |title=Boogeyman 2 is creeping up on us |date=October 11, 2017 |work=[[GamesRadar]] |publisher=[[Future Publishing]] |accessdate=March 27, 2017 }}</ref> The film was slated to start development in January 2007 in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Betancourt wakes up 'The Boogeyman'|url=http://productionweekly.com/2006/10/09/betancourt-wakes-up-the-boogeyman/|website=Production Weekly|accessdate=March 18, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061121184238/http://productionweekly.com/2006/10/09/betancourt-wakes-up-the-boogeyman/|archivedate=November 21, 2006|date=October 9, 2006}}</ref> It was produced by [[Ghost House Pictures]], a film production company created by [[Sam Raimi]] and [[Robert Tapert]] which specializes in creating horror films.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Chapman King|first1=Lynnea|title=The Coen Brothers Encyclopedia|date=October 10, 2014|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=0810885778|page=160}}</ref> Betancourt stated that he wanted to avoid usage of CGI as well as present a new take on the Boogeyman rather than rehashing the storyline of the first film; this led to a more grounded version of the creature in the film. As a result, and due to the film's low budget, he focused especially on the atmosphere and writing.<ref name = \"Betancourt Interview\"/> [[Storyboard]]s were used extensively to plan out the film and minimize wasted effort and resources by make-up artists on unused prosthetics; the limited budget meant that most effects could only be filmed once.<ref name=\"Jeff\">{{cite web|title=Sideshow Collector Q&A: Jeff Betancourt and Boogeyman 2 |url=http://www.sideshowtoy.com/?page_id=3897 |publisher=[[Sideshow Collectibles]] |accessdate=March 23, 2017 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120911185819/http://www.sideshowtoy.com/?page_id=3897 |archivedate=September 11, 2012 |date=November 1, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The former hospital [[Linda Vista Community Hospital]] served as the primary filming location for the [[psychiatric hospital|mental institution]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Riggs |first1=Ransom |title=Strange Geographies: East L.A.'s Abandoned Hospital |url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/18053/strange-geographies-east-las-abandoned-hospital |website=Mental Floss |accessdate=March 27, 2017 |date=2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624074650/http://mentalfloss.com/article/18053/strange-geographies-east-las-abandoned-hospital |archivedate=June 24, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nThe first actor to be cast was [[Renee O'Connor]] as Dr. Jessica Ryan in December 2006;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reneeoconnor.net/news_archive.html |title=Trying my best to be a Bald Christmas Ornament |date=December 20, 2006 |website=Renee O'Connor |last1=O'Connor |first1=Renee |accessdate=March 29, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119224152/http://www.reneeoconnor.net/news_archive.html |archivedate=January 19, 2015 }}</ref> she filmed her first scenes in February 2007.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Day With Renee|url=http://ghosthousepictures.comingsoon.net/news_article.php?articleid=68|publisher=[[Ghost House Pictures]]|accessdate=March 29, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080626080150/http://ghosthousepictures.comingsoon.net/news_article.php?articleid=68|archivedate=June 26, 2008|date=February 8, 2007}}</ref> O'Connor had visited her personal friend and ''Boogeyman''{{'}}s producer [[Rob Tapert]] on the New Zealand set, where she had had a discussion with him about \"the differences of having a supernatural demon versus a real person that can come in and be a threat.\"<ref name = \"O'Connor\"/> She concluded the former was scarier. On getting cast in the film and her approach to the character, she stated:<blockquote>I had a contract with Rob Tapert and I just emailed him and said that I really wanted to play this character. I think she would be interesting because it touches back on some of the things I've played as an actress, and that was it. [...] It was so tight in the dialogue, you just have to play with the relationships and find other things going on with the characters to make it seem like there's more depth to what's going on, that there's more of a history between them.<ref name=\"O'Connor\">{{cite web|last1=Gallagher |first1=Brian |title=Exclusive: Renee O'Connor Dishes on Boogeyman 2 |url=http://movieweb.com/exclusive-renee-oconnor-dishes-on-boogeyman-2/ |work=[[MovieWeb]] |publisher=WATCHR Media, Inc. |accessdate=29 March 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170518191823/http://movieweb.com/exclusive-renee-oconnor-dishes-on-boogeyman-2/ |archivedate=May 18, 2017 }}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn mid-January, [[Danielle Savre]] was cast as the film's lead Laura Porter.<ref>{{cite web|title=Heroes' Danielle Savre Joins the Cast of Boogeyman 2 |url=http://movieweb.com/heroes-danielle-savre-joins-the-cast-of-boogeyman-2/ |work=[[MovieWeb]] |publisher=WATCHR Media, Inc. |5= |accessdate=March 20, 2017 |date=January 17, 2007 }}</ref> On Savre, Betancourt stated that \"[she] has been incredible so far and has been a real trooper. We've [...] had her running up and down these halls screaming, throwing blood on her, throwing vomit on her, throwing guts on her and she's held up so far.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Halfway Home|url=http://ghosthousepictures.comingsoon.net/news_article.php?articleid=69|publisher=[[Ghost House Pictures]]|accessdate=March 27, 2017| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430214715/http://ghosthousepictures.comingsoon.net/news_article.php?articleid=69|archivedate=April 30, 2008|date=February 22, 2007}}</ref> [[Tobin Bell]] was cast as Dr. Mitchell Allen in February<ref>{{cite web|title=Tobin Bell Joins the Cast of Boogeyman 2 |url=http://movieweb.com/tobin-bell-joins-the-cast-of-boogeyman-2/ |publisher=[[MovieWeb]] |accessdate=March 21, 2017 |date=February 5, 2007 }}</ref> and [[Matt Cohen (actor)|Matt Cohen]] as Laura's brother Henry in March.<ref>{{cite web|title=Matt Cohen Gets the Lead in Boogeyman 2 |url=http://movieweb.com/matt-cohen-gets-the-lead-in-boogeyman-2/ |publisher=[[MovieWeb]] |accessdate=March 21, 2017 |date=March 8, 2007 }}</ref> Bell modeled his portrayal after [[Dick Cheney]].<ref name = \"Jeff\"/>\n\n===Effects===\nThe [[special effect]]s were handled by Quantum Creation FX, who were involved with the project throughout the entire duration of filming. Ten artisans and technicians were involved in creating severed heads, puppets, prosthetic makeup, and gore gags.<ref>{{cite web|title=Boogeyman II |url=http://www.quantumcreationfx.com/boogyman-2 |publisher=Quantum Creation FX |accessdate=March 20, 2017 }}</ref> The killer's mask was designed by Jerad S. Marantz,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Marantz |first1=Jerad S. |title=Boogie Man 2 |url=http://jeradsmarantz.blogspot.gr/2010/03/boogie-man-2.html |website=Jerad S. Marantz Design |accessdate=March 21, 2017 |date=March 20, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170103021413/http://jeradsmarantz.blogspot.gr/2010/03/boogie-man-2.html |archivedate=January 3, 2017 }}</ref> and the Boogeyman itself was based on Betancourt's own childhood fears, with \"skeletal things and bird corpses\" as inspiration for its skin texture.<ref name=\"Betancourt Interview\">{{cite web|last1=Gallagher |first1=Brian |title=Exclusive: Jeff Betancourt Talks Boogeyman 2 |url=http://movieweb.com/exclusive-jeff-betancourt-talks-boogeyman-2/ |work=[[MovieWeb]] |publisher=WATCHR Media, Inc. |accessdate=March 23, 2017 |date=January 15, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516162233/http://movieweb.com/exclusive-jeff-betancourt-talks-boogeyman-2/ |archivedate=May 16, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''Boogeyman 2'' was screened in a sold-out showing on October 20, 2007 at the [[Screamfest Horror Film Festival]] in [[Grauman's Chinese Theatre]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Boogeyman 2|url=http://acteva.com/booking.cfm?bevaid=143508|website=Acteva|accessdate=March 19, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013080137/http://acteva.com/booking.cfm?bevaid=143508|archivedate=October 13, 2007}}</ref> During the same month, it was announced that the film would be released on DVD in January 8, 2008.<ref name=\"Boogie 2 IGN\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Boogeyman 2 (Unrated Director's Cut) |url=https://www.amazon.com/Boogeyman-2-Unrated-Directors-Cut/dp/B000XUUQQK/ |publisher=[[Amazon.com|Amazon]] |accessdate=March 31, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160327183032/http://www.amazon.com/Boogeyman-2-Unrated-Directors-Cut/dp/B000XUUQQK |archivedate=March 27, 2016 }}</ref> Outside the [[United States]], the film was released theatrically in both [[Russia]], where it stayed in theaters for two weeks,<ref>{{cite web|title=\u0411\u0443\u0433\u0438\u043c\u0435\u043d 2 |url=https://www.kinopoisk.ru/film/271818/ |website=Kinopoisk |accessdate=March 21, 2017 |language=Russian |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017170353/http://www.kinopoisk.ru/film/271818/ |archivedate=October 17, 2013 }}</ref> and [[Italy]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Calendario film uscita luglio 2008 |url=http://www.mymovies.it/film/uscita/luglio/2008/?p=2 |website=MYmovies.it |accessdate=March 21, 2017 |language=Italian }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Sciallis |first1=Elvezio |title=Recensione: Boogeyman 2 \u2013 Il Ritorno dell'Uomo Nero |url=http://www.latelanera.com/cinema/recensioni/recensione.asp?id=194 |website=LaTeleNera |accessdate=March 21, 2017 |language=Italian |date=July 1, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160914123637/http://www.latelanera.com/cinema/recensioni/recensione.asp?id=194 |archivedate=September 14, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n''Boogeyman 2'' made at least $2,484,219 from its domestic video sales<ref name = \"Gross\"/> and a further $1,798,418 from its international releases, bringing the total gross to $4,282,637.<ref name=\"Int gross\">{{cite web|title=Boogeyman 2 (2007) |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/intl/?page=&id=_fSANSMOI01 |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |publisher=[[Amazon.com]] |accessdate=March 22, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\nThe DVD, which was released as \"Unrated Director's Cut\" and lacks an [[Motion Picture Association of America|MPAA]] rating, includes two different commentaries. The first one features director Betancourt and writer Sieve while the second features actors Bell and Savre along with producers Hein and Bryman. Additionally, the DVD includes a documentary called \"Bringing Fear to Life: Makeup Effects from Storyboards to Screen,\" which shows some of the film's development using storyboards.<ref name=\"Boogie 2 IGN\">{{cite web|title=Boogeyman 2 Announced |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2007/10/16/boogeyman-2-announced |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[j2 Global]] |accessdate=March 19, 2017 |date=October 16, 2007 }}</ref> The film has also been digitally released on [[Google Play]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Boogeyman 2 (2008) |url=https://play.google.com/store/movies/details/Boogeyman_2_2008?id=zgJgIYZOOCI&hl=en |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=March 30, 2017 }}</ref> [[Amazon Video]]<ref>{{cite web\n |title=Boogeyman 2 \n |url=https://www.amazon.com/Boogeyman-2-Danielle-Savre/dp/B00B7C3DN6/ \n |publisher=[[Amazon.com|Amazon]] \n |accessdate=March 31, 2017 \n |url-status=live \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160216195806/http://www.amazon.com/Boogeyman-2-Danielle-Savre/dp/B00B7C3DN6 \n |archivedate=February 16, 2016 \n}}</ref> and [[Hulu]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Vick |first1=Megan |title=Here's what's coming (and leaving) Hulu in June 2017 |url=http://www.kfvs12.com/story/35447954/heres-whats-coming-and-leaving-hulu-in-june-2017 |website=KFVS12 |accessdate=May 18, 2017 |date=May 17, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523053837/http://www.kfvs12.com/story/35447954/heres-whats-coming-and-leaving-hulu-in-june-2017 |archivedate=May 23, 2017}}</ref> It's was released on Blu-ray by Shout Factory's Scream Factory in July 14, 2020.\n\n==Reception==\nThe film was criticized for having an unoriginal story and unlikable characters. Brandon Ciampaglia of [[IGN]] described it as \"yet another stupid horror film\" and gave it a score of 4/10.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ciampaglia |first1=Brandon |title=DVD Screamers, Vol. 8 |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2008/01/03/dvd-screamers-vol-8 |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[j2 Global]] |accessdate=March 18, 2017 |date=January 3, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170106105404/http://www.ign.com/articles/2008/01/03/dvd-screamers-vol-8 |archivedate=January 6, 2017 }}</ref> Ryan Turek of [[CraveOnline|ComingSoon.net]] criticized the story, characters, and lack of suspense, but found the film more entertaining than the original, with better acting than it deserved. He added that despite the movie's low budget, \"[Betancourt] has hashed together a fine-looking film that\u2019s technically competent.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Turek |first1=Ryan |title=Boogeyman 2 |url=http://www.comingsoon.net/horror/news/708076-boogeyman-2 |work=[[ComingSoon.net]] |publisher=[[CraveOnline]] |accessdate=March 27, 2017 |date=October 23, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170327232035/http://www.comingsoon.net/horror/news/708076-boogeyman-2 |archivedate=March 27, 2017 }}</ref> Tristan Sinns of [[Dread Central]] awarded it two out of five stars, criticizing it for not featuring the mythological [[Boogeyman]] and having unsympathetic characters but praising the death scenes as \"rather creative.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sinns |first1=Tristan |title=Boogeyman 2 (2008) |url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/reviews/5364/boogeyman-2-2008/ |work=[[Dread Central]] |publisher=Dread Central Media, LLC |accessdate=April 27, 2017 |date=November 2, 2007 |df= }}</ref>\n\nPositive reviews praised the film for presenting a more realistic approach to the Boogeyman and eschewing CGI, both of which were considered improvements over its predecessor. Its death scenes were highly praised for being extremely violent and gory. Many reviewers also recognized that the film exceeded their expectations despite its direct-to-video status and low budget. Shawn Lealos of ''[[CHUD.com]]'' gave the film a score of 6.8 out of ten, stating that it was \"a very solid little horror flick that forgoes the ridiculous CGI and hokum supernatural aspects of the first movie, as well as the restraints of PG-13.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lealos |first1=Shawn S. |title=DVD Review: Boogeyman 2 |url=http://www.chud.com/13662/dvd-review-boogeyman-2/ |website=[[CHUD.com]] |accessdate=March 27, 2017 |date=February 15, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170518083315/http://www.chud.com/13662/dvd-review-boogeyman-2/ |archivedate=May 18, 2017 }}</ref> In a similar review, Matthew Stern of ''[[PopMatters]]'' praised the film in comparison to its predecessor, giving it eight stars out of ten, with a consensus reading: \"A film that bucks the stigma of direct-to-DVD sequels, this unyieldingly dark and bloody feature will surprise you, especially if you were unfortunate enough to catch the first one.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stern |first1=Matthew A. |title=Boogeyman 2 |url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/boogeyman-2/ |website=[[PopMatters]] |accessdate=March 27, 2017 |date=January 22, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170106102447/http://www.popmatters.com/review/boogeyman-2/ |archivedate=January 6, 2017 }}</ref> David Nusair of Reel Film Reviews also praised ''Boogeyman 2'' over the first film, particularly for its \"satisfying kill sequences\" and an entertaining supporting cast. While he criticized the middle half as \"uneventful,\" he felt that the film \"recovers nicely for a surprisingly enthralling third act\" and gave it 2.5/4 stars.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Nusair |first1=David |title=Sony's January '08 Releases |url=http://www.reelfilm.com/snyjan08.htm#boog |publisher=Reel Film Reviews |accessdate=March 29, 2017 |date=January 15, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611215644/http://www.reelfilm.com/snyjan08.htm |archivedate=June 11, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Sequel==\n{{Main|Boogeyman 3}}\nA sequel, titled ''Boogeyman 3,'' premiered at the [[Screamfest Horror Film Festival]] on October 18, 2008<ref>{{cite web|title=Boogeyman 3 DVD Details! |url=http://iconsoffright.com/news/2008/10/boogeyman_3_dvd_details.html |website=Icons of Fright |accessdate=April 20, 2017 |date=October 17, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510092305/http://iconsoffright.com/news/2008/10/boogeyman_3_dvd_details.html |archivedate=May 10, 2017 }}</ref> and was released [[direct-to-video]] in January 20, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gallagher |first1=Brian |title=Boogeyman 3 Brings the Terror Back to DVD on January 20th |url=http://movieweb.com/boogeyman-3-brings-the-terror-back-to-dvd-on-january-20th/ |work=[[MovieWeb]] |publisher=WATCHR Media, Inc. |accessdate=April 20, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510120407/http://movieweb.com/boogeyman-3-brings-the-terror-back-to-dvd-on-january-20th/ |archivedate=May 10, 2017 }}</ref> Brian Sieve came back as writer, but the film features new cast members and characters, taking place on a college campus and starring [[Erin Cahill]]. As with the first movie, the Boogeyman is portrayed as a supernatural entity.<ref>{{cite web|title=Boogeyman 3 |url=http://www.hollywood.com/movies/boogeyman-3-59209640/ |website=Hollywood |accessdate=April 20, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170421001916/http://www.hollywood.com/movies/boogeyman-3-59209640/ |archivedate=April 21, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Film|Speculative fiction/Horror}}\n* {{official website|http://www.sonypictures.com/movies/boogeyman2/index.html}}\n* {{IMDb title|0900357|Boogeyman 2}}\n* {{Allmovie|388061|Boogeyman 2}}\n\n{{Boogeyman}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boogeyman 2}}\n[[Category:2000s sequel films]]\n[[Category:2007 horror films]]\n[[Category:2007 direct-to-video films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American supernatural horror films]]\n[[Category:Direct-to-video sequel films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films based on urban legends]]\n[[Category:Films about fear]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the 2007 horror film|the unrelated 1983 film|Boogeyman II}}\n{{featured article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Boogeyman 2\n| image = Boogeyman2.jpg\n| alt = Poster feature the film's lead, a young blonde woman, lying on a bed and facing the camera with the Boogeyman being under her bed.\n| caption = DVD cover\n| director = [[Jeff Betancourt]]\n| producer = {{plainlist|\n* Steve Hein\n* Gary Bryman\n}}\n| writer = Brian Sieve\n| starring = {{plainlist|\n* [[Danielle Savre]]\n* [[Matt Cohen (actor)|Matt Cohen]]\n* [[David Gallagher]]\n* [[Mae Whitman]]\n* [[Renee O'Connor]]\n* [[Tobin Bell]]\n}}\n| music = [[Joseph LoDuca]]\n| cinematography = Nelson Cragg\n| editing = Jeff Betancourt\n| studio = [[Ghost House Pictures]]\n| distributor = [[Sony Pictures Home Entertainment]]\n| released = {{Film date|2007|10|20|Screamfest Horror Film Festival|2008|01|08|United States|2008|06|05|Russia}}\n| runtime = 89 minutes<ref>{{cite web|title=Boogeyman 2 (2007) |url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/boogeyman-2-2007 |publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |accessdate=May 22, 2017 }}</ref>\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| budget = $4.5 million<ref>{{cite web|title=Boogeyman 2 |url=http://bloody-disgusting.com/horrordb/movies/boogeyman-2/ |work=[[Bloody Disgusting]] |publisher=The Collective |accessdate=March 19, 2017 }}</ref>\n| gross = $4.3 million<ref name=\"Gross\">{{cite web|title=Boogeyman (2008) |url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Boogeyman-2#tab=video-sales |website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |publisher=Nash Information Services, LLC |accessdate=March 18, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150920005749/http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Boogeyman-2 |archivedate=September 20, 2015 }}</ref><ref name = \"Int gross\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''Boogeyman 2''''' is a 2007 American [[supernatural horror film]] edited and directed by [[Jeff Betancourt]] and the [[sequel]] to the 2005 film ''[[Boogeyman (film)|Boogeyman]]''. The film was written by Brian Sieve and stars [[Danielle Savre]], [[Matt Cohen (actor)|Matt Cohen]], [[Tobin Bell]] and [[Renee O'Connor]]. Savre portrays Laura Porter, a woman who witnessed her parents' murder alongside her brother as a child. She believes the killer to be the [[Bogeyman|Boogeyman]], and now as an adult seeks group therapy to overcome her phobia of the creature. However, her fears become reality as her fellow patients are murdered one by one.\n\nDue to the previous film's financial success, ''Boogeyman 2'' was announced in October 2006. Production of the film began in the same month with the hiring of Betancourt as director and Sieve attached as writer. Casting began in December of the same year with the hiring of O'Connor; Savre got the lead role in January 2007. Filming took place in [[Los Angeles]] at the former hospital, [[Linda Vista Community Hospital]], over a four-month period, beginning in January 2007 and concluding in April. Unlike the original film, which featured the Boogeyman as a supernatural being, Betancourt strove to present a more grounded and realistic version of the mythical creature. Additionally, emphasis was placed on the writing and atmosphere to compensate for the film's small $4.5 million budget.\n\nAfter screening at the [[Screamfest Horror Film Festival]] on October 20, 2007, ''Boogeyman 2'' was released [[direct-to-video]] in the United States on January 8, 2008; it was later released theatrically in Russia and Italy. It received mixed reviews from critics, although many of them considered it to be a general improvement over its predecessor. Attention was especially given to the human-like nature of the Boogeyman in the film, which reviewers felt was preferable to monsters in other contemporary [[Creature Features|creature features]], including the previous film. Despite a mediocre commercial performance, recouping slightly less than its budget, the film received a sequel, ''[[Boogeyman 3]]'', the following year.\n\n==Plot==\nAs young children Laura Porter and her brother Henry witness their parents' brutal murder by a hooded man, whom they believe to be the [[Bogeyman|Boogeyman]]. As an adult, Henry has attended group therapy, improving such that he is instead currently looking for work. Laura joins this group as he leaves, meeting the other members: [[Nyctophobia|nyctophobic]] Mark, [[Germaphobia|germaphobic]] Paul, [[Self-harm|masochistic]] Alison, [[Agoraphobia|agoraphobic]] and commitment-averse Darren, and Nicky, a [[bulimic]] girl who fears extreme weight gain.\n\nUpon her joining, however, the members of the group are targeted and murdered one by one. All of their deaths relate to their fears: Mark falls down an elevator shaft, trying to escape from the darkness when the lights go out, and is torn in half. Paul accidentally consumes a cockroach while eating a bag of chips; he is given cleaning solution by a masked figure, and upon drinking it, burns a hole in his throat. Laura begins to suspect these deaths are not accidental. The hospital loses power, leaving Laura, Alison, Darren, Nicky, Dr. Jessica Ryan, and the receptionist Gloria in the dark. Gloria goes to the basement to turn the lights back on, but once the patients return to their rooms, Alison is tied to her bed by the Boogeyman. He places maggots on her arms, which burrow into her skin via her self-inflicted incisions, and she kills herself attempting to cut them out.\n\nDr. Ryan goes to the basement to check on Gloria, but is electrocuted by the Boogeyman while standing in a puddle of water. Laura finds a file on her brother and those of other patients with bogyphobia ([[phobia]] of the Boogeyman). She learns that all bogyphobia patients - including Tim Jensen, the protagonist of the first film - have committed suicide after being treated by Dr. Mitchell Allen. Darren and Nicky have sex in the locker room as Laura finds Alison; she alerts them to Alison's corpse, but they find upon returning that the blood and maggots have been cleaned up, leading them to believe that Laura is [[Hallucination|hallucinating]]. Darren and Nicky go to his room, where they argue about the viability of their relationship. Darren forces Nicky out of his room, and is then attacked by the Boogeyman, who disembowels him and removes his heart.\n\nLaura finds Nicky on a basement table with hoses attached to her, pumping bile into her body until she explodes. The Boogeyman chases Laura through the hospital; along the way she finds Gloria's body and Dr. Ryan, barely alive and mumbling in a trance-like state. She also runs into Dr. Allen, who believes Laura committed the killings. He tries to sedate her, but is stopped by the Boogeyman, who stabs him and shoves two needles into his eyes. The Boogeyman is revealed to be Henry; Dr. Allen had locked him in a closet in an attempt to treat him of his bogyphobia, and the Boogeyman possessed Henry at that time. The chase ends when Laura decapitates the Boogeyman with gardening shears. The police arrive and discover that under the Boogeyman mask was Dr. Ryan; after killing Dr. Allen but prior to chasing Laura, Henry put the mask on the doctor and escaped. Laura realizes that Henry is running free and is framed for the murders and arrested.\n\nIn a [[post-credits scene]], the Boogeyman looks at a picture of Laura and Henry as adults before disappearing.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Danielle Savre]] as Laura Porter\n* [[Matt Cohen (actor)|Matt Cohen]] as Henry Porter\n* [[Tobin Bell]] as Dr. Mitchell Allen\n* [[Renee O'Connor]] as Dr. Jessica Ryan\n* Chrissy Griffith as Nicky\n* [[Michael Graziadei]] as Darren\n* [[Mae Whitman]] as Alison\n* [[Johnny Simmons]] as Paul\n* [[David Gallagher]] as Mark\n* [[Lesli Margherita]] as Gloria\n* [[Tom Lenk]] as Perry\n* [[Sammi Hanratty]] as Young Laura Porter\n* Jarrod Bailey as Young Henry Porter\n* Lucas Fleischer as Mr. Porter\n* Suzanne Jamieson as Mrs. Porter\n* Christopher John Fields as Detective\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development and filming===\n[[File:Boogeyman 2 - Boogie Mask.jpg<!-- Don't resize non-free images per WP:NFCCP -->|thumb|right|Evolution of the killer's mask, dubbed \"Boogie Mask\", throughout various stages of development. Ranging from concept art (''left''), to early build (''center'') and the finished product (''right'').|alt=Three images showing featuring the killer wearing a mask in: a drawing (left), mold (center) and final film design (right). The mask covers the entire face and has huge teeth where the mouth is. In the final film, the killer also wears a black hoodie.]]\n\n''Boogeyman 2'' was first announced in October 2006 due to the financial success of its predecessor with [[Jeff Betancourt]], [[film editing|film editor]] of ''[[The Exorcism of Emily Rose]]'', ''[[When a Stranger Calls (2006 film)|When a Stranger Calls]]'' and ''[[The Grudge 2]],'' making his directorial debut and Brian Sieve attached as writer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/boogeyman-2-is-creeping-up-on-us/ |title=Boogeyman 2 is creeping up on us |date=October 11, 2017 |work=[[GamesRadar]] |publisher=[[Future Publishing]] |accessdate=March 27, 2017 }}</ref> The film was slated to start development in January 2007 in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Betancourt wakes up 'The Boogeyman'|url=http://productionweekly.com/2006/10/09/betancourt-wakes-up-the-boogeyman/|website=Production Weekly|accessdate=March 18, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061121184238/http://productionweekly.com/2006/10/09/betancourt-wakes-up-the-boogeyman/|archivedate=November 21, 2006|date=October 9, 2006}}</ref> It was produced by [[Ghost House Pictures]], a film production company created by [[Sam Raimi]] and [[Robert Tapert]] which specializes in creating horror films.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Chapman King|first1=Lynnea|title=The Coen Brothers Encyclopedia|date=October 10, 2014|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=0810885778|page=160}}</ref> Betancourt stated that he wanted to avoid usage of CGI as well as present a new take on the Boogeyman rather than rehashing the storyline of the first film; this led to a more grounded version of the creature in the film. As a result, and due to the film's low budget, he focused especially on the atmosphere and writing.<ref name = \"Betancourt Interview\"/> [[Storyboard]]s were used extensively to plan out the film and minimize wasted effort and resources by make-up artists on unused prosthetics; the limited budget meant that most effects could only be filmed once.<ref name=\"Jeff\">{{cite web|title=Sideshow Collector Q&A: Jeff Betancourt and Boogeyman 2 |url=http://www.sideshowtoy.com/?page_id=3897 |publisher=[[Sideshow Collectibles]] |accessdate=March 23, 2017 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120911185819/http://www.sideshowtoy.com/?page_id=3897 |archivedate=September 11, 2012 |date=November 1, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The former hospital [[Linda Vista Community Hospital]] served as the primary filming location for the [[psychiatric hospital|mental institution]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Riggs |first1=Ransom |title=Strange Geographies: East L.A.'s Abandoned Hospital |url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/18053/strange-geographies-east-las-abandoned-hospital |website=Mental Floss |accessdate=March 27, 2017 |date=2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624074650/http://mentalfloss.com/article/18053/strange-geographies-east-las-abandoned-hospital |archivedate=June 24, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nThe first actor to be cast was [[Renee O'Connor]] as Dr. Jessica Ryan in December 2006;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reneeoconnor.net/news_archive.html |title=Trying my best to be a Bald Christmas Ornament |date=December 20, 2006 |website=Renee O'Connor |last1=O'Connor |first1=Renee |accessdate=March 29, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119224152/http://www.reneeoconnor.net/news_archive.html |archivedate=January 19, 2015 }}</ref> she filmed her first scenes in February 2007.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Day With Renee|url=http://ghosthousepictures.comingsoon.net/news_article.php?articleid=68|publisher=[[Ghost House Pictures]]|accessdate=March 29, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080626080150/http://ghosthousepictures.comingsoon.net/news_article.php?articleid=68|archivedate=June 26, 2008|date=February 8, 2007}}</ref> O'Connor had visited her personal friend and ''Boogeyman''{{'}}s producer [[Rob Tapert]] on the New Zealand set, where she had had a discussion with him about \"the differences of having a supernatural demon versus a real person that can come in and be a threat.\"<ref name = \"O'Connor\"/> She concluded the former was scarier. On getting cast in the film and her approach to the character, she stated:<blockquote>I had a contract with Rob Tapert and I just emailed him and said that I really wanted to play this character. I think she would be interesting because it touches back on some of the things I've played as an actress, and that was it. [...] It was so tight in the dialogue, you just have to play with the relationships and find other things going on with the characters to make it seem like there's more depth to what's going on, that there's more of a history between them.<ref name=\"O'Connor\">{{cite web|last1=Gallagher |first1=Brian |title=Exclusive: Renee O'Connor Dishes on Boogeyman 2 |url=http://movieweb.com/exclusive-renee-oconnor-dishes-on-boogeyman-2/ |work=[[MovieWeb]] |publisher=WATCHR Media, Inc. |accessdate=29 March 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170518191823/http://movieweb.com/exclusive-renee-oconnor-dishes-on-boogeyman-2/ |archivedate=May 18, 2017 }}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn mid-January, [[Danielle Savre]] was cast as the film's lead Laura Porter.<ref>{{cite web|title=Heroes' Danielle Savre Joins the Cast of Boogeyman 2 |url=http://movieweb.com/heroes-danielle-savre-joins-the-cast-of-boogeyman-2/ |work=[[MovieWeb]] |publisher=WATCHR Media, Inc. |5= |accessdate=March 20, 2017 |date=January 17, 2007 }}</ref> On Savre, Betancourt stated that \"[she] has been incredible so far and has been a real trooper. We've [...] had her running up and down these halls screaming, throwing blood on her, throwing vomit on her, throwing guts on her and she's held up so far.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Halfway Home|url=http://ghosthousepictures.comingsoon.net/news_article.php?articleid=69|publisher=[[Ghost House Pictures]]|accessdate=March 27, 2017| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430214715/http://ghosthousepictures.comingsoon.net/news_article.php?articleid=69|archivedate=April 30, 2008|date=February 22, 2007}}</ref> [[Tobin Bell]] was cast as Dr. Mitchell Allen in February<ref>{{cite web|title=Tobin Bell Joins the Cast of Boogeyman 2 |url=http://movieweb.com/tobin-bell-joins-the-cast-of-boogeyman-2/ |publisher=[[MovieWeb]] |accessdate=March 21, 2017 |date=February 5, 2007 }}</ref> and [[Matt Cohen (actor)|Matt Cohen]] as Laura's brother Henry in March.<ref>{{cite web|title=Matt Cohen Gets the Lead in Boogeyman 2 |url=http://movieweb.com/matt-cohen-gets-the-lead-in-boogeyman-2/ |publisher=[[MovieWeb]] |accessdate=March 21, 2017 |date=March 8, 2007 }}</ref> Bell modeled his portrayal after [[Dick Cheney]].<ref name = \"Jeff\"/>\n\n===Effects===\nThe [[special effect]]s were handled by Quantum Creation FX, who were involved with the project throughout the entire duration of filming. Ten artisans and technicians were involved in creating severed heads, puppets, prosthetic makeup, and gore gags.<ref>{{cite web|title=Boogeyman II |url=http://www.quantumcreationfx.com/boogyman-2 |publisher=Quantum Creation FX |accessdate=March 20, 2017 }}</ref> The killer's mask was designed by Jerad S. Marantz,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Marantz |first1=Jerad S. |title=Boogie Man 2 |url=http://jeradsmarantz.blogspot.gr/2010/03/boogie-man-2.html |website=Jerad S. Marantz Design |accessdate=March 21, 2017 |date=March 20, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170103021413/http://jeradsmarantz.blogspot.gr/2010/03/boogie-man-2.html |archivedate=January 3, 2017 }}</ref> and the Boogeyman itself was based on Betancourt's own childhood fears, with \"skeletal things and bird corpses\" as inspiration for its skin texture.<ref name=\"Betancourt Interview\">{{cite web|last1=Gallagher |first1=Brian |title=Exclusive: Jeff Betancourt Talks Boogeyman 2 |url=http://movieweb.com/exclusive-jeff-betancourt-talks-boogeyman-2/ |work=[[MovieWeb]] |publisher=WATCHR Media, Inc. |accessdate=March 23, 2017 |date=January 15, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516162233/http://movieweb.com/exclusive-jeff-betancourt-talks-boogeyman-2/ |archivedate=May 16, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''Boogeyman 2'' was screened in a sold-out showing on October 20, 2007 at the [[Screamfest Horror Film Festival]] in [[Grauman's Chinese Theatre]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Boogeyman 2|url=http://acteva.com/booking.cfm?bevaid=143508|website=Acteva|accessdate=March 19, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013080137/http://acteva.com/booking.cfm?bevaid=143508|archivedate=October 13, 2007}}</ref> During the same month, it was announced that the film would be released on DVD in January 8, 2008.<ref name=\"Boogie 2 IGN\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Boogeyman 2 (Unrated Director's Cut) |url=https://www.amazon.com/Boogeyman-2-Unrated-Directors-Cut/dp/B000XUUQQK/ |publisher=[[Amazon.com|Amazon]] |accessdate=March 31, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160327183032/http://www.amazon.com/Boogeyman-2-Unrated-Directors-Cut/dp/B000XUUQQK |archivedate=March 27, 2016 }}</ref> Outside the [[United States]], the film was released theatrically in both [[Russia]], where it stayed in theaters for two weeks,<ref>{{cite web|title=\u0411\u0443\u0433\u0438\u043c\u0435\u043d 2 |url=https://www.kinopoisk.ru/film/271818/ |website=Kinopoisk |accessdate=March 21, 2017 |language=Russian |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017170353/http://www.kinopoisk.ru/film/271818/ |archivedate=October 17, 2013 }}</ref> and [[Italy]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Calendario film uscita luglio 2008 |url=http://www.mymovies.it/film/uscita/luglio/2008/?p=2 |website=MYmovies.it |accessdate=March 21, 2017 |language=Italian }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Sciallis |first1=Elvezio |title=Recensione: Boogeyman 2 \u2013 Il Ritorno dell'Uomo Nero |url=http://www.latelanera.com/cinema/recensioni/recensione.asp?id=194 |website=LaTeleNera |accessdate=March 21, 2017 |language=Italian |date=July 1, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160914123637/http://www.latelanera.com/cinema/recensioni/recensione.asp?id=194 |archivedate=September 14, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n''Boogeyman 2'' made at least $2,484,219 from its domestic video sales<ref name = \"Gross\"/> and a further $1,798,418 from its international releases, bringing the total gross to $4,282,637.<ref name=\"Int gross\">{{cite web|title=Boogeyman 2 (2007) |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/intl/?page=&id=_fSANSMOI01 |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |publisher=[[Amazon.com]] |accessdate=March 22, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\nThe DVD, which was released as \"Unrated Director's Cut\" and lacks an [[Motion Picture Association of America|MPAA]] rating, includes two different commentaries. The first one features director Betancourt and writer Sieve while the second features actors Bell and Savre along with producers Hein and Bryman. Additionally, the DVD includes a documentary called \"Bringing Fear to Life: Makeup Effects from Storyboards to Screen,\" which shows some of the film's development using storyboards.<ref name=\"Boogie 2 IGN\">{{cite web|title=Boogeyman 2 Announced |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2007/10/16/boogeyman-2-announced |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[j2 Global]] |accessdate=March 19, 2017 |date=October 16, 2007 }}</ref> The film has also been digitally released on [[Google Play]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Boogeyman 2 (2008) |url=https://play.google.com/store/movies/details/Boogeyman_2_2008?id=zgJgIYZOOCI&hl=en |publisher=[[Google]] |accessdate=March 30, 2017 }}</ref> [[Amazon Video]]<ref>{{cite web\n |title=Boogeyman 2 \n |url=https://www.amazon.com/Boogeyman-2-Danielle-Savre/dp/B00B7C3DN6/ \n |publisher=[[Amazon.com|Amazon]] \n |accessdate=March 31, 2017 \n |url-status=live \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160216195806/http://www.amazon.com/Boogeyman-2-Danielle-Savre/dp/B00B7C3DN6 \n |archivedate=February 16, 2016 \n}}</ref> and [[Hulu]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Vick |first1=Megan |title=Here's what's coming (and leaving) Hulu in June 2017 |url=http://www.kfvs12.com/story/35447954/heres-whats-coming-and-leaving-hulu-in-june-2017 |website=KFVS12 |accessdate=May 18, 2017 |date=May 17, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523053837/http://www.kfvs12.com/story/35447954/heres-whats-coming-and-leaving-hulu-in-june-2017 |archivedate=May 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe film was criticized for having an unoriginal story and unlikable characters. Brandon Ciampaglia of [[IGN]] described it as \"yet another stupid horror film\" and gave it a score of 4/10.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ciampaglia |first1=Brandon |title=DVD Screamers, Vol. 8 |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2008/01/03/dvd-screamers-vol-8 |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[j2 Global]] |accessdate=March 18, 2017 |date=January 3, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170106105404/http://www.ign.com/articles/2008/01/03/dvd-screamers-vol-8 |archivedate=January 6, 2017 }}</ref> Ryan Turek of [[CraveOnline|ComingSoon.net]] criticized the story, characters, and lack of suspense, but found the film more entertaining than the original, with better acting than it deserved. He added that despite the movie's low budget, \"[Betancourt] has hashed together a fine-looking film that\u2019s technically competent.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Turek |first1=Ryan |title=Boogeyman 2 |url=http://www.comingsoon.net/horror/news/708076-boogeyman-2 |work=[[ComingSoon.net]] |publisher=[[CraveOnline]] |accessdate=March 27, 2017 |date=October 23, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170327232035/http://www.comingsoon.net/horror/news/708076-boogeyman-2 |archivedate=March 27, 2017 }}</ref> Tristan Sinns of [[Dread Central]] awarded it two out of five stars, criticizing it for not featuring the mythological [[Boogeyman]] and having unsympathetic characters but praising the death scenes as \"rather creative.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sinns |first1=Tristan |title=Boogeyman 2 (2008) |url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/reviews/5364/boogeyman-2-2008/ |work=[[Dread Central]] |publisher=Dread Central Media, LLC |accessdate=April 27, 2017 |date=November 2, 2007 |df= }}</ref>\n\nPositive reviews praised the film for presenting a more realistic approach to the Boogeyman and eschewing CGI, both of which were considered improvements over its predecessor. Its death scenes were highly praised for being extremely violent and gory. Many reviewers also recognized that the film exceeded their expectations despite its direct-to-video status and low budget. Shawn Lealos of ''[[CHUD.com]]'' gave the film a score of 6.8 out of ten, stating that it was \"a very solid little horror flick that forgoes the ridiculous CGI and hokum supernatural aspects of the first movie, as well as the restraints of PG-13.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lealos |first1=Shawn S. |title=DVD Review: Boogeyman 2 |url=http://www.chud.com/13662/dvd-review-boogeyman-2/ |website=[[CHUD.com]] |accessdate=March 27, 2017 |date=February 15, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170518083315/http://www.chud.com/13662/dvd-review-boogeyman-2/ |archivedate=May 18, 2017 }}</ref> In a similar review, Matthew Stern of ''[[PopMatters]]'' praised the film in comparison to its predecessor, giving it eight stars out of ten, with a consensus reading: \"A film that bucks the stigma of direct-to-DVD sequels, this unyieldingly dark and bloody feature will surprise you, especially if you were unfortunate enough to catch the first one.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stern |first1=Matthew A. |title=Boogeyman 2 |url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/boogeyman-2/ |website=[[PopMatters]] |accessdate=March 27, 2017 |date=January 22, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170106102447/http://www.popmatters.com/review/boogeyman-2/ |archivedate=January 6, 2017 }}</ref> David Nusair of Reel Film Reviews also praised ''Boogeyman 2'' over the first film, particularly for its \"satisfying kill sequences\" and an entertaining supporting cast. While he criticized the middle half as \"uneventful,\" he felt that the film \"recovers nicely for a surprisingly enthralling third act\" and gave it 2.5/4 stars.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Nusair |first1=David |title=Sony's January '08 Releases |url=http://www.reelfilm.com/snyjan08.htm#boog |publisher=Reel Film Reviews |accessdate=March 29, 2017 |date=January 15, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611215644/http://www.reelfilm.com/snyjan08.htm |archivedate=June 11, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Sequel==\n{{Main|Boogeyman 3}}\nA sequel, titled ''Boogeyman 3,'' premiered at the [[Screamfest Horror Film Festival]] on October 18, 2008<ref>{{cite web|title=Boogeyman 3 DVD Details! |url=http://iconsoffright.com/news/2008/10/boogeyman_3_dvd_details.html |website=Icons of Fright |accessdate=April 20, 2017 |date=October 17, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510092305/http://iconsoffright.com/news/2008/10/boogeyman_3_dvd_details.html |archivedate=May 10, 2017 }}</ref> and was released [[direct-to-video]] in January 20, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gallagher |first1=Brian |title=Boogeyman 3 Brings the Terror Back to DVD on January 20th |url=http://movieweb.com/boogeyman-3-brings-the-terror-back-to-dvd-on-january-20th/ |work=[[MovieWeb]] |publisher=WATCHR Media, Inc. |accessdate=April 20, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510120407/http://movieweb.com/boogeyman-3-brings-the-terror-back-to-dvd-on-january-20th/ |archivedate=May 10, 2017 }}</ref> Brian Sieve came back as writer, but the film features new cast members and characters, taking place on a college campus and starring [[Erin Cahill]]. As with the first movie, the Boogeyman is portrayed as a supernatural entity.<ref>{{cite web|title=Boogeyman 3 |url=http://www.hollywood.com/movies/boogeyman-3-59209640/ |website=Hollywood |accessdate=April 20, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170421001916/http://www.hollywood.com/movies/boogeyman-3-59209640/ |archivedate=April 21, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Film|Speculative fiction/Horror}}\n* {{official website|http://www.sonypictures.com/movies/boogeyman2/index.html}}\n* {{IMDb title|0900357|Boogeyman 2}}\n* {{Allmovie|388061|Boogeyman 2}}\n\n{{Boogeyman}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boogeyman 2}}\n[[Category:2000s sequel films]]\n[[Category:2007 horror films]]\n[[Category:2007 direct-to-video films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American supernatural horror films]]\n[[Category:Direct-to-video sequel films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films based on urban legends]]\n[[Category:Films about fear]]\n", "name_user": "206.174.161.30", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHome media:Blu-ray)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boogeyman_2"}
{"title_page": "John Wick (character)", "text_new": "{{Short description|Character in John Wick, played by Keanu Reeves}} \n{{Infobox character\n| franchise          = [[John Wick]]\n| color              = #800080\n| name               = John Wick\n| image              = John Wick Keanu.jpeg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Keanu Reeves as John Wick in ''[[John Wick: Chapter 2]]'' (2017)\n| series             = <!-- or |franchise=; use without the italic on the outside -->\n| first              = ''[[John Wick (film)|John Wick]]'' (2014)\n| last               = \n| creator            = [[Derek Kolstad]]\n| designer           = \n| portrayer          = [[Keanu Reeves]]\n| voice              = \n| motion_actor       = \n| full_name          = Jonathan Wick\n| nickname           = Baba Yaga / The Boogeyman\n| position           = [[Protagonist]]\n| gender             = Male\n| title              = Assassin\n| occupation         = {{Plainlist|\n\n* Hitman (formerly)\n* Vigilante\n}}\n| affiliation        = <!-- or |alignment= -->\n| fighting_style     = {{Plainlist| \n* [[Jujutsu|Japanese Jiu-jitsu]]\n* [[Brazilian jiu-jitsu]]\n* [[Judo]]\n* [[Sambo (martial art)|Sambo]]\n}}\n| weapon             = \n| family             = \n| spouse             =\n* Helen Wick (deceased)\n\n| significant_other  = <!-- or |significant_others= -->\n| children           \n| relatives          = \n| religion           = \n| origin             = <!-- or |home= -->\n| nationality        = American\n}}\n\n'''John Wick''' is the fictional title character and main protagonist of the [[John Wick|''John Wick'' film series]]. He is portrayed by [[Keanu Reeves]]. The character of John Wick, originally named '''Jardani Jovonovich''', is an assassin who has long retired, until a gang invades his house, steals his car and kills his dog, setting him on a near unstoppable path of ducks and revenge, after which a former colleague (William Legg) calls in a \"marker\" to have him fulfill an assassination leading to him being pursued by the entirety of the High Table of Assassins.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.insider.com/how-keanu-reeves-learned-to-shoot-guns-2019-7 |title=How Keanu Reeves learned to shoot guns for 'John Wick' |first1=Joe |last1=Avella |first2=Conner |last2=Blake |date=August 13, 2019 |website=Insider |language=en |accessdate=September 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nJohn Wick was once named Jardani Jovonovich, born in former Soviet Russia to parents who were of Romani, Russian, Ukrainian and [[Koryo saram]] descent. He was orphaned at a young age for unknown reasons before taken in by his father's old friend, who would eventually become his mentor.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.spin.com/2019/05/john-wick-3-review/ |title=John Wick 3 Isn't Just About Fighting, It's About Fame and Fandom |first=Will |last=Gottsegen |date=May 20, 2019 |website=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |access-date=September 7, 2019}}</ref> He was adopted by the [[Ruska Roma]] organization from [[Belarus]] and raised by their leader ''The Director'' in their New York headquarters. Under the supervision of The Director, Jardani was trained as an assassin; he learned multiple skills including [[martial arts]], firearms, edged weapons, improvised weapons, tactical driving, infiltration, [[escapology]] and more. At some point Jardani took the name \"John Wick\" and left the Ruska Roma. He became a feared and ruthless [[contract killing|hitman]] his targets would call \"[[Baba Yaga]]\". Wick was noted for his great focus and determination; his fighting prowess was such that he once single-handedly killed three men with a pencil. Eventually John met a woman named Helen and [[Falling in love|fell in love]]. Hoping to leave his past as a contract killer behind him and pursue a normal life, John met with crime boss Viggo Tarasov, who agreed to grant him his wish if he could accomplish a task described as \"impossible\" by others. In order to accomplish this task John required assistance from [[Camorra]] member Santino D'Antonio and subsequently ended up owing a blood debt to him. Viggo Tarasov said the killings Wick performed laid the foundations for what his criminal organization became, implying Wick eliminated all his major rivals for him. After completing his \"impossible task,\" John Wick retired as an assassin and settled down with his wife Helen.\n\n===''John Wick''===\n{{Main page|John Wick (film)}}\nFollowing his wife's terminal illness, John prefers to remain isolated from society. He spends his days driving his prized car \u2014 a 1969 [[Ford Mustang Mach 1]] \u2014 and caring for his new dog, Daisy, the last gift from his dearly departed wife. This changes when Iosef Tarasov assaults John, steals his car and kills Daisy. This sets John on a rampage of slaughter and vengeance. Attempting to protect his son from John's rampage, Viggo sends assassins to stop John, but all are killed. Eventually John takes his revenge, killing both Iosef and Viggo. After he does this, John rescues a pitbull puppy scheduled to be euthanized from an [[animal shelter]].\n\n===''John Wick: Chapter 2''===\n{{Main page|John Wick: Chapter 2}}\nAfter exacting his vengeance on the Tarasovs, John retrieves his prized car from Abram Tarasov and forms a truce with him allowing him to live. John hopes to return to retirement but this is interrupted by Santino D'Antonio, who asks for him to complete his blood oath and assassinate his sister, Gianna, allowing Santino to have a seat at The High Table. Wick reluctantly travels to Rome to fulfill the task, only to realize that he will be Santino's next target for eliminating a member of The High Table. Santino sends his bodyguard Ares and Gianna's former bodyguard Cassian after Wick but both ultimately fail. Santino places a $7 million bounty on Wick's head, after which Wick enlists assistance from The Bowery King, who supplies him with a gun that carries only 7 bullets and information of Santino's location. John eventually finds Santino in the safe grounds of The Continental. Santino taunts John as The Continental Owner, Winston, advises John to walk away before he breaks the laws of The Continental. Despite this, John still assassinates Santino, leaving John to be declared \"excommunicado\" for conducting business on Continental Grounds. Winston allows John one hour to escape before the contract is doubled and his status is rescinded from all services.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2019/05/20/john-wick-chapter-4-keanu-reeves-fourth-movie-coming/3748121002/ |title='John Wick 4' underway, but don't expect a happy ending for Keanu Reeves |first=Bryan |last=Alexander |date=May 24, 2019 |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |language=en |accessdate=September 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===''John Wick: Chapter 3 \u2013 Parabellum''===\n{{Main page|John Wick: Chapter 3 \u2013 Parabellum}}\nExcommunicated, exhausted, and injured, John spends his one-hour head start preparing to flee from New York, as assassins gather and hear word of the bounty on John for killing a member of the High Table. John escapes to Morocco, meets with former ally Sofia, and calls in a favor to be brought to the Elder, a man above the High Table, who can clear the bounty. John travels the desert to the point of collapse in order for The Elder to find him. The Elder agrees to grant him forgiveness from the bounty in return for killing Winston and serving the High Table for the rest of his life; John severs his ring finger and offers his wedding ring to The Elder to show his commitment. John returns to New York and is pursued by assassins until he reaches the safe haven of the Continental. John reunites with Winston but decides not to kill him. Instead John and the hotel's concierge Charon make a stand against the High Table and their enforcers. Successfully defeating waves of attackers, Winston and High Table representative The Adjudicator parley on the hotel roof. Ultimately, Winston shoots John to restore his standing with the High Table and John tumbles from the roof into the street. The Bowery King, recovering from grave wounds inflicted by The Adjudicator's assassin, collects the badly injured John and brings him to his hideout, where he tells John he intends to rise up against the High Table. He asks John if he is also \"pissed off.\" John replies \"Yeah.\"\n\n==Characterization==\nThe character and franchise has been described as a \"central [[Bogeyman|boogeyman]] character who can\u2019t be killed\" and a \"modern, [[Action film|action-oriented]] equivalent of '80s horror franchises\", and reportedly has a [[Body count|kill count]] of 306, exceeding [[Jason Voorhees]] and [[Michael Myers (Halloween)|Michael Myers]] combined.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3562954/just-three-movies-john-wick-killed-people-jason-michaels-combined-total/ |title=In Just Three Movies, John Wick Has Killed More People Than Jason and Michael's Combined Total |first=John |last=Squires |date=May 23, 2019 |website=[[Bloody Disgusting]] |access-date=July 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2471894/john-wick-kill-count-all-the-kills-in-all-3-movies |title=John Wick Kill Count: All The Kills In All 3 Movies |first=Eric |last=Eisenberg |date=May 17, 2019 |website=CinemaBlend |access-date=July 20, 2019}}</ref> Wick's violent one-man crusade has been described as an extreme case of [[workplace revenge]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.inverse.com/article/27783-john-wick-chapter-2-dog-revenge-psychology-retaliation-guns-rage |title=John Wick Suffers Extreme Workplace Rage, Psychologist Says |last=Hutchinson |first=Sean |date=February 13, 2017 |website=[[Inverse (website)|Inverse]] |access-date=July 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nSince the franchise's inception, the character of John Wick and his development in subsequent sequels have been seen as a reinvigoration of Keanu Reeves's career. The films have a cult following and Reeves's portrayal of the character has been praised.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/may/18/john-wick-chapter-3-parabellum-review-keanu-reeves |title=John Wick: Chapter 3 - Parabellum review - The Art of Action |first=Wendy |last=Ide |date=May 19, 2019 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |language=en |accessdate=September 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web |title=John Wick (2014)  - Trivia - IMDb |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2911666/trivia |website=[[Internet Movie Database]] |accessdate=11 October 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180409202736/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt2911666/trivia |archivedate=9 April 2018}}\n*{{cite web |last1=Bean |first1=Travis |title=The Reason People Connect So Deeply With John Wick |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/travisbean/2019/09/12/the-reason-people-connect-so-deeply-with-john-wick/ |website=[[Forbes]] |accessdate=11 October 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190912191208/https://www.forbes.com/sites/travisbean/2019/09/12/the-reason-people-connect-so-deeply-with-john-wick/ |archivedate=12 September 2019 |date=12 September 2019}}\n*[https://globalfilmlocations.net/2017/04/23/john-wick-2-film-locations/ Film Locations]\n{{John Wick}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wick, John}}\n[[Category:John Wick (franchise)]]\n[[Category:Film characters introduced in 2014]]\n[[Category:Martial artists characters in films]]\n[[Category:Fictional American people of Eastern European descent]]\n[[Category:Fictional assassins]]\n[[Category:Fictional Dait\u014d-ry\u016b Aiki-j\u016bjutsu practitioners]]\n[[Category:Fictional Brazilian jiu-jitsu practitioners]]\n[[Category:Fictional judoka]]\n[[Category:Fictional jujutsuka]]\n[[Category:Fictional karateka]]\n[[Category:Fictional wushu practitioners]]\n[[Category:Fictional Krav Maga practitioners]]\n[[Category:Fictional Belarusian people]]\n[[Category:Fictional melee weapons practitioners]]\n[[Category:Fictional marksmen and snipers]]\n[[Category:Fictional mass murderers]]\n[[Category:Fictional orphans]]\n[[Category:Fictional Romani people]]\n[[Category:Fictional sambo practitioners]]\n[[Category:Fictional vigilantes]]\n[[Category:Fictional United States Marine Corps personnel]]\n[[Category:Action film characters]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Character in John Wick, played by Keanu Reeves}} \n{{Infobox character\n| franchise          = [[John Wick]]\n| color              = #800080\n| name               = John Wick\n| image              = John Wick Keanu.jpeg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Keanu Reeves as John Wick in ''[[John Wick: Chapter 2]]'' (2017)\n| series             = <!-- or |franchise=; use without the italic on the outside -->\n| first              = ''[[John Wick (film)|John Wick]]'' (2014)\n| last               = \n| creator            = [[Derek Kolstad]]\n| designer           = \n| portrayer          = [[Keanu Reeves]]\n| voice              = \n| motion_actor       = \n| full_name          = Jonathan Wick\n| nickname           = Baba Yaga / The Boogeyman\n| position           = [[Protagonist]]\n| gender             = Male\n| title              = Assassin\n| occupation         = {{Plainlist|\n\n* Hitman (formerly)\n* Vigilante\n}}\n| affiliation        = <!-- or |alignment= -->\n| fighting_style     = {{Plainlist| \n* [[Jujutsu|Japanese Jiu-jitsu]]\n* [[Brazilian jiu-jitsu]]\n* [[Judo]]\n* [[Sambo (martial art)|Sambo]]\n}}\n| weapon             = \n| family             = \n| spouse             =\n* Helen Wick (deceased)\n\n| significant_other  = <!-- or |significant_others= -->\n| children           \n| relatives          = \n| religion           = \n| origin             = <!-- or |home= -->\n| nationality        = American\n}}\n\n'''John Wick''' is the fictional title character and main protagonist of the [[John Wick|''John Wick'' film series]]. He is portrayed by [[Keanu Reeves]]. The character of John Wick, originally named '''Jardani Jovonovich''', is an assassin who has long retired, until a gang invades his house, steals his car and kills his dog, setting him on a near unstoppable path of revenge, after which a former colleague (William Legg) calls in a \"marker\" to have him fulfill an assassination leading to him being pursued by the entirety of the High Table of Assassins.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.insider.com/how-keanu-reeves-learned-to-shoot-guns-2019-7 |title=How Keanu Reeves learned to shoot guns for 'John Wick' |first1=Joe |last1=Avella |first2=Conner |last2=Blake |date=August 13, 2019 |website=Insider |language=en |accessdate=September 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nJohn Wick was once named Jardani Jovonovich, born in former Soviet Russia to parents who were of Romani, Russian, Ukrainian and [[Koryo saram]] descent. He was orphaned at a young age for unknown reasons before taken in by his father's old friend, who would eventually become his mentor.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.spin.com/2019/05/john-wick-3-review/ |title=John Wick 3 Isn't Just About Fighting, It's About Fame and Fandom |first=Will |last=Gottsegen |date=May 20, 2019 |website=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |access-date=September 7, 2019}}</ref> He was adopted by the [[Ruska Roma]] organization from [[Belarus]] and raised by their leader ''The Director'' in their New York headquarters. Under the supervision of The Director, Jardani was trained as an assassin; he learned multiple skills including [[martial arts]], firearms, edged weapons, improvised weapons, tactical driving, infiltration, [[escapology]] and more. At some point Jardani took the name \"John Wick\" and left the Ruska Roma. He became a feared and ruthless [[contract killing|hitman]] his targets would call \"[[Baba Yaga]]\". Wick was noted for his great focus and determination; his fighting prowess was such that he once single-handedly killed three men with a pencil. Eventually John met a woman named Helen and [[Falling in love|fell in love]]. Hoping to leave his past as a contract killer behind him and pursue a normal life, John met with crime boss Viggo Tarasov, who agreed to grant him his wish if he could accomplish a task described as \"impossible\" by others. In order to accomplish this task John required assistance from [[Camorra]] member Santino D'Antonio and subsequently ended up owing a blood debt to him. Viggo Tarasov said the killings Wick performed laid the foundations for what his criminal organization became, implying Wick eliminated all his major rivals for him. After completing his \"impossible task,\" John Wick retired as an assassin and settled down with his wife Helen.\n\n===''John Wick''===\n{{Main page|John Wick (film)}}\nFollowing his wife's terminal illness, John prefers to remain isolated from society. He spends his days driving his prized car \u2014 a 1969 [[Ford Mustang Mach 1]] \u2014 and caring for his new dog, Daisy, the last gift from his dearly departed wife. This changes when Iosef Tarasov assaults John, steals his car and kills Daisy. This sets John on a rampage of slaughter and vengeance. Attempting to protect his son from John's rampage, Viggo sends assassins to stop John, but all are killed. Eventually John takes his revenge, killing both Iosef and Viggo. After he does this, John rescues a pitbull puppy scheduled to be euthanized from an [[animal shelter]].\n\n===''John Wick: Chapter 2''===\n{{Main page|John Wick: Chapter 2}}\nAfter exacting his vengeance on the Tarasovs, John retrieves his prized car from Abram Tarasov and forms a truce with him allowing him to live. John hopes to return to retirement but this is interrupted by Santino D'Antonio, who asks for him to complete his blood oath and assassinate his sister, Gianna, allowing Santino to have a seat at The High Table. Wick reluctantly travels to Rome to fulfill the task, only to realize that he will be Santino's next target for eliminating a member of The High Table. Santino sends his bodyguard Ares and Gianna's former bodyguard Cassian after Wick but both ultimately fail. Santino places a $7 million bounty on Wick's head, after which Wick enlists assistance from The Bowery King, who supplies him with a gun that carries only 7 bullets and information of Santino's location. John eventually finds Santino in the safe grounds of The Continental. Santino taunts John as The Continental Owner, Winston, advises John to walk away before he breaks the laws of The Continental. Despite this, John still assassinates Santino, leaving John to be declared \"excommunicado\" for conducting business on Continental Grounds. Winston allows John one hour to escape before the contract is doubled and his status is rescinded from all services.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2019/05/20/john-wick-chapter-4-keanu-reeves-fourth-movie-coming/3748121002/ |title='John Wick 4' underway, but don't expect a happy ending for Keanu Reeves |first=Bryan |last=Alexander |date=May 24, 2019 |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |language=en |accessdate=September 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===''John Wick: Chapter 3 \u2013 Parabellum''===\n{{Main page|John Wick: Chapter 3 \u2013 Parabellum}}\nExcommunicated, exhausted, and injured, John spends his one-hour head start preparing to flee from New York, as assassins gather and hear word of the bounty on John for killing a member of the High Table. John escapes to Morocco, meets with former ally Sofia, and calls in a favor to be brought to the Elder, a man above the High Table, who can clear the bounty. John travels the desert to the point of collapse in order for The Elder to find him. The Elder agrees to grant him forgiveness from the bounty in return for killing Winston and serving the High Table for the rest of his life; John severs his ring finger and offers his wedding ring to The Elder to show his commitment. John returns to New York and is pursued by assassins until he reaches the safe haven of the Continental. John reunites with Winston but decides not to kill him. Instead John and the hotel's concierge Charon make a stand against the High Table and their enforcers. Successfully defeating waves of attackers, Winston and High Table representative The Adjudicator parley on the hotel roof. Ultimately, Winston shoots John to restore his standing with the High Table and John tumbles from the roof into the street. The Bowery King, recovering from grave wounds inflicted by The Adjudicator's assassin, collects the badly injured John and brings him to his hideout, where he tells John he intends to rise up against the High Table. He asks John if he is also \"pissed off.\" John replies \"Yeah.\"\n\n==Characterization==\nThe character and franchise has been described as a \"central [[Bogeyman|boogeyman]] character who can\u2019t be killed\" and a \"modern, [[Action film|action-oriented]] equivalent of '80s horror franchises\", and reportedly has a [[Body count|kill count]] of 306, exceeding [[Jason Voorhees]] and [[Michael Myers (Halloween)|Michael Myers]] combined.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3562954/just-three-movies-john-wick-killed-people-jason-michaels-combined-total/ |title=In Just Three Movies, John Wick Has Killed More People Than Jason and Michael's Combined Total |first=John |last=Squires |date=May 23, 2019 |website=[[Bloody Disgusting]] |access-date=July 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2471894/john-wick-kill-count-all-the-kills-in-all-3-movies |title=John Wick Kill Count: All The Kills In All 3 Movies |first=Eric |last=Eisenberg |date=May 17, 2019 |website=CinemaBlend |access-date=July 20, 2019}}</ref> Wick's violent one-man crusade has been described as an extreme case of [[workplace revenge]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.inverse.com/article/27783-john-wick-chapter-2-dog-revenge-psychology-retaliation-guns-rage |title=John Wick Suffers Extreme Workplace Rage, Psychologist Says |last=Hutchinson |first=Sean |date=February 13, 2017 |website=[[Inverse (website)|Inverse]] |access-date=July 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nSince the franchise's inception, the character of John Wick and his development in subsequent sequels have been seen as a reinvigoration of Keanu Reeves's career. The films have a cult following and Reeves's portrayal of the character has been praised.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/may/18/john-wick-chapter-3-parabellum-review-keanu-reeves |title=John Wick: Chapter 3 - Parabellum review - The Art of Action |first=Wendy |last=Ide |date=May 19, 2019 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |language=en |accessdate=September 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web |title=John Wick (2014)  - Trivia - IMDb |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2911666/trivia |website=[[Internet Movie Database]] |accessdate=11 October 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180409202736/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt2911666/trivia |archivedate=9 April 2018}}\n*{{cite web |last1=Bean |first1=Travis |title=The Reason People Connect So Deeply With John Wick |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/travisbean/2019/09/12/the-reason-people-connect-so-deeply-with-john-wick/ |website=[[Forbes]] |accessdate=11 October 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190912191208/https://www.forbes.com/sites/travisbean/2019/09/12/the-reason-people-connect-so-deeply-with-john-wick/ |archivedate=12 September 2019 |date=12 September 2019}}\n*[https://globalfilmlocations.net/2017/04/23/john-wick-2-film-locations/ Film Locations]\n{{John Wick}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wick, John}}\n[[Category:John Wick (franchise)]]\n[[Category:Film characters introduced in 2014]]\n[[Category:Martial artists characters in films]]\n[[Category:Fictional American people of Eastern European descent]]\n[[Category:Fictional assassins]]\n[[Category:Fictional Dait\u014d-ry\u016b Aiki-j\u016bjutsu practitioners]]\n[[Category:Fictional Brazilian jiu-jitsu practitioners]]\n[[Category:Fictional judoka]]\n[[Category:Fictional jujutsuka]]\n[[Category:Fictional karateka]]\n[[Category:Fictional wushu practitioners]]\n[[Category:Fictional Krav Maga practitioners]]\n[[Category:Fictional Belarusian people]]\n[[Category:Fictional melee weapons practitioners]]\n[[Category:Fictional marksmen and snipers]]\n[[Category:Fictional mass murderers]]\n[[Category:Fictional orphans]]\n[[Category:Fictional Romani people]]\n[[Category:Fictional sambo practitioners]]\n[[Category:Fictional vigilantes]]\n[[Category:Fictional United States Marine Corps personnel]]\n[[Category:Action film characters]]\n", "name_user": "2601:204:d880:70e0:8480:6d2f:a8eb:d382", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Cars)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Wick_(character)"}
