o, only numeric characters-->\n| acceleration_mph     = <!--Final speed in mph may contain only numeric characters-->\n| acceleration_km/h    = <!--Final speed in km/h may contain only numeric characters-->\n| acceleration_in      = <!--Number of seconds may contain words -->\n| gforce               =\n| restriction_ft       = <!--Must be expressed in feet and may contain only numeric characters.-->\n| restriction_in       = 56<!--Must be expressed in inches and may contain only numeric characters.-->\n| restriction_cm       = <!--Must be expressed in centimetres and may contain only numeric characters.-->\n| trains               = <!--Must contain only numeric characters.-->\n| carspertrain         = 1<!--Must contain only numeric characters.-->\n| rowspercar           = 2<!--Must contain only numeric characters.-->\n| ridersperrow         = 1<!--Must contain only numeric characters.-->\n| website              =http://www.smokymountainalpinecoaster.com/ \n| rcdb_number          = 13322\n}}\n\n'''Smoky Mountain Alpine Coaster''' is a [[mountain coaster]] located in [[Pigeon Forge, Tennessee]].<ref>{{cite web\n | url =http://www.smokymountainalpinecoaster.com/\n | title =Smoky Mountain Alpine Coaster\n | last =\n | first =\n | date =\n | website =Smoky Mountain Alpine Coaster\n | publisher =\n | access-date =9 March 2017\n | quote = }}</ref> It opened on August 3, 2013, and was the first mountain coaster to be built in the [[Great Smoky Mountains|Smoky Mountains]]. The coaster is the longest mountain coaster in the United States. {{cn}}\n\n==History==\n\nThe owners began looking to open an mountain coaster in the U.S. in 2010, with the area being pinpointed in 2011. Construction began on the coaster in January 2013, with its opening in August of that year.<ref>{{Citation\n | last =Williams \n | first =Michael\n | author-link =\n | last2 =\n | first2 =\n | author2-link =\n | title =Mountain coasters in national park offer the newest fun in Tennessee\n | newspaper =\n | pages =\n | year =\n | date =25 May 2015\n | url =http://www.newsnet5.com/lifestyle/family/mountain-coasters-in-national-park-offer-the-newest-fun-in-tennessee\n | archive-url =\n | archive-date =\n | access-date = 9 March 2017 }}</ref>\n<ref>{{Cite rcdb\n | coaster_name=Alpine Coaster\n | newspaper =\n | pages =\n | year =\n | date =\n | rcdb_number=13322\n|location=Smoky Mountain Alpine Coaster\n | archive-url =\n | archive-date =\n | access-date =19 March 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nOne to two riders sit in individual carts, which are pulled to the top of a mountain by the means of a cable. Once released at the top, the cart navigates twists and turns down the mountain on a secured rail. Unlike a conventional [[roller coaster]], the cars are equipped with hand brakes, which allow the riders to control their speed. Additionally, the carts themselves have a magnetic braking system to prevent the cart from going too fast.<ref>{{Citation\n | last =Williams \n | first =Michael\n | author-link =\n | last2 =\n | first2 =\n | author2-link =\n | title =Mountain coasters in national park offer the newest fun in Tennessee\n | newspaper =\n | pages =\n | year =\n | date =25 May 2015\n | url =http://www.newsnet5.com/lifestyle/family/mountain-coasters-in-national-park-offer-the-newest-fun-in-tennessee\n | archive-url =\n | archive-date =\n | access-date = 9 March 2017 }}\n\n</ref> The ride also has LED lighting for night rides, with over 300,000 lights.<ref>{{Citation\n | last =Leshock\n | first =Marcus\n | author-link =\n | last2 =\n | first2 =\n | author2-link =\n | title =Coastin\u2019 the Country: Pigeon Forge Alpine Coasters\n | newspaper =\n | pages =\n | year =\n | date =17 March 2017\n | url =http://wgntv.com/2017/03/17/coastin-the-country-pigeon-forge-alpine-coasters/\n | archive-url =\n | archive-date =\n | access-date = 30 March 2017 }}\n\n</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n", "name_user": "ProgHead777", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smoky_Mountain_Alpine_Coaster"}
{"title_page": "Michael Green (New York lawyer)", "text_new": "'''Michael Charles Green''' (born 1961) is the executive commissioner of the [[New York State Division of Criminal Justice Services]] (DCJS). He is the former District Attorney for [[Monroe County, New York]]. During 2011, he was a federal judicial nominee for the [[United States District Court for the Western District of New York]], and although he was reported out of committee to the floor of the [[United States Senate]], Green never received a floor vote, and President Obama did not renominate him in the next session of Congress. Michael Green has been accused of retaliating against women for speaking up about sexual harassment at the Division of Criminal Justice Services. [https://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/news/politics/albany/2018/12/27/michael-green-dcjs-harassment-claims/2421750002/]\n\n==Early life and education==\nA native of [[Henrietta, New York]], Green attended [[McQuaid Jesuit High School]] in [[Rochester, New York]].<ref name=nydailyrecord_20030521>{{cite news | url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4180/is_20030521/ai_n10068344/ | title=Mike Green receives nod in Monroe County District Attorney race | first= | last=Daily Record Staff | work=The Daily Record | date=May 21, 2003 | accessdate=January 30, 2011}}</ref> He received a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree from [[LeMoyne College]] in [[Syracuse, New York]] in 1983.<ref name=nydailyrecord_20030521/> Green then earned his [[Juris Doctor]] from [[Western New England College School of Law]] in 1986.<ref name=nylj_20110128>{{cite news | url=http://www.law.com/jsp/nylj/PubArticleNY.jsp?id=1202479602680&District_Attorney_General_Counsel_Are_Nominated_for_Federal_Bench | title=District Attorney, General Counsel Are Nominated for Federal Bench | first=Michael J. | last=Paquette | work=[[New York Law Journal]] | date=January 28, 2011 | accessdate=January 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nGreen joined the Monroe County district attorney's office in 1987.<ref name=nylj_20110128/> In 2001, Monroe County District Attorney Howard Relin appointed Green to be first assistant district attorney.<ref name=nylj_20110128/><ref name=dem_and_chron_20110127>{{cite news | url=http://www.democratandchronicle.com/article/20110127/NEWS01/101270324/1002/NEWS | title=Barack Obama nominates Michael Green for federal bench | first=Gary | last=Craig | work=[[Democrat and Chronicle]] | date=January 27, 2011 | accessdate=January 30, 2011}}</ref> Green was elected as Monroe County District Attorney in 2003, after Relin chose not to seek reelection.<ref name=dem_and_chron_20110127/>\n\nGreen had been a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] prior to running for office in 2003, but the party was not supportive of his candidacy.<ref name=dem_and_chron_20110127/> Green won election in 2003 after switching to the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]].<ref name=dem_and_chron_20110127/>\n\nPrior to being elected District Attorney, Green served as an Assistant District Attorney for 17 years.  For the three years before his election, he served as the First Assistant District Attorney, responsible for the homicide prosecutions in Monroe County. \n\nHe has served in numerous other capacities in the office, including as the Capital Crimes Prosecutor, Deputy Chief of the Major Felony Bureau, Chief of the DWI Bureau, and trial attorney in the Major Felony Bureau. He has tried over 100 jury trials, and has prosecuted 40 homicide cases. He has been lead prosecutor on four first degree murder cases, including one of the few capital cases to end with a death sentence in New York. As District Attorney, Green continues to personally prosecute homicide and other high-profile cases.\n\n==Judicial nomination==\nIn July 2010, [[List of United States Senators from New York|New York Senator]] [[Charles Schumer]] recommended Green to fill a vacancy on the [[United States District Court for the Western District of New York]].<ref name=dem_and_chron_20110127/> On January 26, 2011, President [[Barack Obama]] formally nominated Green to a judgeship on the Western District of New York.<ref name=dem_and_chron_20110127/> Green would have filled the vacancy created by Judge [[David G. Larimer]].<ref name=nydailyrecord_20110128>{{cite news | url=http://nydailyrecord.com/blog/2011/01/28/senate-approval-next-for-green%E2%80%99s-judgeship/ | title=Senate approval next for Green\u2019s judgeship | first=Denise M. | last=Champagne | work=The Daily Record | date=January 28, 2011 | accessdate=January 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\nGreen's nomination was voted out of the [[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary]] in June 2011, but his nomination languished on the Senate floor for the next six months. Utah Sen. [[Mike Lee (U.S. politician)|Mike Lee]] was the lone senator to oppose Green in the committee vote, and no Republican senators publicly explained their opposition to his nomination.  In follow-up questions to his hearing testimony, however, several Republican senators focused on Green's decision to seek drug treatment rather than jail for some offenders, while others queried Green about his views on the death penalty.\n\nUltimately, at the behest of Senate Republicans, Green's nomination was one of a small number of executive and judicial branch nominations to be returned to President Obama on December 17, 2011, pursuant to the rules of the Senate.<ref name=\"Senate Record for December 17, 2011\">[http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/B?r112:@FIELD%28FLD003+s%29+@FIELD%28DDATE+20111217%29 Senate Record for December 17, 2011]</ref>  On December 18, 2011, a White House spokesman told a local newspaper that Obama would not be renominating Green to the seat.  \"Mike Green would have made an outstanding judge and it is very unfortunate not only for him, but for a strong judiciary, that partisan politics stood in the way,\" Schumer said in a statement on December 18, 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.13wham.com/news/local/story/monroe-county-rocheser-mike-green-judgeship-denied/OkCbxgqgQ0qpZnKcqip9kw.cspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-12-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120203210352/http://www.13wham.com/news/local/story/monroe-county-rocheser-mike-green-judgeship-denied/OkCbxgqgQ0qpZnKcqip9kw.cspx |archivedate=2012-02-03 }}</ref> <ref>http://www.democratandchronicle.com/article/20111219/NEWS01/112190322</ref>\n\nOn December 19, 2011, Green said at a press conference that he blamed local opposition on his failed judicial nomination, as a result of his prosecution of public corruption.  \"I'm proud of the decisions I've made as DA,\u201d Green said.  \"I can hold my head up high and leave this office.\"<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">http://www.democratandchronicle.com/article/20111219/NEWS01/111219012/DA-Mike-Green-blames-politics-scuttling-nomination?odyssey=tab|topnews|text|Home</ref>\n\n== After the judicial nomination ==\n\nGreen completed his term as district attorney at the end of December 2011.  He did not seek re-election in November 2011.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>  \n\nIn February 2012, New York Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] named Green as Executive Commissioner of the New York State Division of Criminal Justice Services (DCJS).<ref name=\"DCJS release\">{{cite press release | url=http://www.governor.ny.gov/press/02132012ExecutiveDeputyCommissioner | title=Governor Cuomo Announces Former Monroe County District Attorney Mike Green to Serve as DCJS Executive Deputy Commissioner | publisher=New York Governor's Press Office | date=13 February 2012 | accessdate = 2 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Barack Obama judicial appointment controversies]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Green, Michael}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Le Moyne College alumni]]\n[[Category:Western New England University alumni]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:People from Henrietta, New York]]\n", "text_old": "'''Michael Charles Green''' (born 1961) is the executive commissioner of the [[New York State Division of Criminal Justice Services]] (DCJS). He is the former District Attorney for [[Monroe County, New York]]. During 2011, he was a federal judicial nominee for the [[United States District Court for the Western District of New York]], and although he was reported out of committee to the floor of the [[United States Senate]], Green never received a floor vote, and President Obama did not renominate him in the next session of Congress.\n\n==Early life and education==\nA native of [[Henrietta, New York]], Green attended [[McQuaid Jesuit High School]] in [[Rochester, New York]].<ref name=nydailyrecord_20030521>{{cite news | url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4180/is_20030521/ai_n10068344/ | title=Mike Green receives nod in Monroe County District Attorney race | first= | last=Daily Record Staff | work=The Daily Record | date=May 21, 2003 | accessdate=January 30, 2011}}</ref> He received a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree from [[LeMoyne College]] in [[Syracuse, New York]] in 1983.<ref name=nydailyrecord_20030521/> Green then earned his [[Juris Doctor]] from [[Western New England College School of Law]] in 1986.<ref name=nylj_20110128>{{cite news | url=http://www.law.com/jsp/nylj/PubArticleNY.jsp?id=1202479602680&District_Attorney_General_Counsel_Are_Nominated_for_Federal_Bench | title=District Attorney, General Counsel Are Nominated for Federal Bench | first=Michael J. | last=Paquette | work=[[New York Law Journal]] | date=January 28, 2011 | accessdate=January 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nGreen joined the Monroe County district attorney's office in 1987.<ref name=nylj_20110128/> In 2001, Monroe County District Attorney Howard Relin appointed Green to be first assistant district attorney.<ref name=nylj_20110128/><ref name=dem_and_chron_20110127>{{cite news | url=http://www.democratandchronicle.com/article/20110127/NEWS01/101270324/1002/NEWS | title=Barack Obama nominates Michael Green for federal bench | first=Gary | last=Craig | work=[[Democrat and Chronicle]] | date=January 27, 2011 | accessdate=January 30, 2011}}</ref> Green was elected as Monroe County District Attorney in 2003, after Relin chose not to seek reelection.<ref name=dem_and_chron_20110127/>\n\nGreen had been a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] prior to running for office in 2003, but the party was not supportive of his candidacy.<ref name=dem_and_chron_20110127/> Green won election in 2003 after switching to the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]].<ref name=dem_and_chron_20110127/>\n\nPrior to being elected District Attorney, Green served as an Assistant District Attorney for 17 years.  For the three years before his election, he served as the First Assistant District Attorney, responsible for the homicide prosecutions in Monroe County. \n\nHe has served in numerous other capacities in the office, including as the Capital Crimes Prosecutor, Deputy Chief of the Major Felony Bureau, Chief of the DWI Bureau, and trial attorney in the Major Felony Bureau. He has tried over 100 jury trials, and has prosecuted 40 homicide cases. He has been lead prosecutor on four first degree murder cases, including one of the few capital cases to end with a death sentence in New York. As District Attorney, Green continues to personally prosecute homicide and other high-profile cases.\n\n==Judicial nomination==\nIn July 2010, [[List of United States Senators from New York|New York Senator]] [[Charles Schumer]] recommended Green to fill a vacancy on the [[United States District Court for the Western District of New York]].<ref name=dem_and_chron_20110127/> On January 26, 2011, President [[Barack Obama]] formally nominated Green to a judgeship on the Western District of New York.<ref name=dem_and_chron_20110127/> Green would have filled the vacancy created by Judge [[David G. Larimer]].<ref name=nydailyrecord_20110128>{{cite news | url=http://nydailyrecord.com/blog/2011/01/28/senate-approval-next-for-green%E2%80%99s-judgeship/ | title=Senate approval next for Green\u2019s judgeship | first=Denise M. | last=Champagne | work=The Daily Record | date=January 28, 2011 | accessdate=January 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\nGreen's nomination was voted out of the [[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary]] in June 2011, but his nomination languished on the Senate floor for the next six months. Utah Sen. [[Mike Lee (U.S. politician)|Mike Lee]] was the lone senator to oppose Green in the committee vote, and no Republican senators publicly explained their opposition to his nomination.  In follow-up questions to his hearing testimony, however, several Republican senators focused on Green's decision to seek drug treatment rather than jail for some offenders, while others queried Green about his views on the death penalty.\n\nUltimately, at the behest of Senate Republicans, Green's nomination was one of a small number of executive and judicial branch nominations to be returned to President Obama on December 17, 2011, pursuant to the rules of the Senate.<ref name=\"Senate Record for December 17, 2011\">[http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/B?r112:@FIELD%28FLD003+s%29+@FIELD%28DDATE+20111217%29 Senate Record for December 17, 2011]</ref>  On December 18, 2011, a White House spokesman told a local newspaper that Obama would not be renominating Green to the seat.  \"Mike Green would have made an outstanding judge and it is very unfortunate not only for him, but for a strong judiciary, that partisan politics stood in the way,\" Schumer said in a statement on December 18, 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.13wham.com/news/local/story/monroe-county-rocheser-mike-green-judgeship-denied/OkCbxgqgQ0qpZnKcqip9kw.cspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-12-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120203210352/http://www.13wham.com/news/local/story/monroe-county-rocheser-mike-green-judgeship-denied/OkCbxgqgQ0qpZnKcqip9kw.cspx |archivedate=2012-02-03 }}</ref> <ref>http://www.democratandchronicle.com/article/20111219/NEWS01/112190322</ref>\n\nOn December 19, 2011, Green said at a press conference that he blamed local opposition on his failed judicial nomination, as a result of his prosecution of public corruption.  \"I'm proud of the decisions I've made as DA,\u201d Green said.  \"I can hold my head up high and leave this office.\"<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">http://www.democratandchronicle.com/article/20111219/NEWS01/111219012/DA-Mike-Green-blames-politics-scuttling-nomination?odyssey=tab|topnews|text|Home</ref>\n\n== After the judicial nomination ==\n\nGreen completed his term as district attorney at the end of December 2011.  He did not seek re-election in November 2011.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>  \n\nIn February 2012, New York Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] named Green as Executive Commissioner of the New York State Division of Criminal Justice Services (DCJS).<ref name=\"DCJS release\">{{cite press release | url=http://www.governor.ny.gov/press/02132012ExecutiveDeputyCommissioner | title=Governor Cuomo Announces Former Monroe County District Attorney Mike Green to Serve as DCJS Executive Deputy Commissioner | publisher=New York Governor's Press Office | date=13 February 2012 | accessdate = 2 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Barack Obama judicial appointment controversies]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Green, Michael}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Le Moyne College alumni]]\n[[Category:Western New England University alumni]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:People from Henrietta, New York]]\n", "name_user": "Patriot2020", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update to include lawsuit against Michael Green", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Green_(New_York_lawyer)"}
